sity Actors Meet the Universal Bard / rDawson, Anthony B. -- t11. Canadian Bacon / rYachnin, Paul / Whitted, Brent E. -- t12. Canada, Negative Capability, Cymbeline / rLeggatt, Alexander -- t13. Frye's Shakespeare, Frye's Canada / rFindlay, L.M. -- tPART FOUR. Reimagining Shakespaeare -- t14. Nation and/as Adaptation: Shakespeare, Canada, and Authenticity / rFischlin, Daniel -- t15. Undead and Unsafe: Adapting Shakespeare (in Canada) / rFortier, Mark -- t16. Normand Chaurette's Les Reiner. Shakespeare and the Modern in the Alchemical Oven / rSherlow, Lois -- t17. Othello in Three Times / rKnowles, Rig -- tAfterword. Relocating Shakespeare, Redefining Canada / rBrydon, Diana -- tAppendix. Research Opportunities in Canadian Shakespeare / rSchagerl, Jessica -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs there a distinctly Canadian Shakespeare? What is the status and function of Shakespeare in various locations within the nation: at Stratford, on CBC radio, in regional and university theatres, in Canadian drama and popular culture? Shakespeare in Canada brings insights from a little explored but extensive archive to contemporary debates about the cultural uses of Shakespeare and what it means to be Canadian.Canada's long history of Shakespeare productions and reception, including adaptations, literary reworkings, and parodies, is analysed and contextualized within the four sections of the book. A timely addition to the growing field that studies the transnational reach of Shakespeare across cultures, this collection examines the political and cultural agendas invoked not only by Shakespeare's plays, but also by his very name. In part a historical and regional survey of Shakespeare in performance, adaptation, and criticism, this is the first work to engage Shakespeare with distinctly Canadian debates addressing nationalism, separatism, cultural appropriation, cultural nationalism, feminism, and postcolonialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh1 aBrydon, Diana, eeditor.1 aMakaryk, Irena, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442679870423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442679870.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG